Value.value: Mining operations face many dangerous obstacles and poisonous gases are one of the deadliest. Seldom detectable by sight or smell, a cloud of toxic gas can kill an entire crew of mine workers in short order. Worse, sometimes these gases can build up pressure behind veins or in reservoirs, and once struck lead to massive explosions. Competent miners used caged animals to detect these gases, but if the corpses laying on the mine floor here are any indication, these were incompetent miners. It stings your eyes and nostrils even from a few feet away, so it is best to leave before you join them.
The air here stings your eyes and nostrils. If you don't get out of here soon, you'll be sick. Or dead, if the corpses laying on the mine floor are any indication.

Mining operations face many obstacles and poisonous gases are one of the deadliest. Seldom detectable by sight or smell, toxic gas can kill an entire crew of mine workers in short order. Worse, sometimes these gases can build up pressure behind veins or in reservoirs, and once struck lead to massive explosions. Competent miners used caged animals to detect these gases. Small fey creatures: a fairy or pixie is preferred, because their natural glow can undergo easily observable spectral shifts when dying from toxic gas. Mites are far more affordable; they have no natural glow, but their dramatic gasping and pleading serves a similar warning function. If the corpses on the mine floor here are any indication, these miners were unprepared for the fate which befell them. This particular gas is clearly toxic and even from several feet away it stings your eyes and nostrils. The greenish-yellow haze suggests a chlorine byproduct, but you would require a sample to be certain.

value.0: "The darkness is cold and everlasting, but provides a dark mantle for the blade in the night. With silent stride and hidden hand, cull the weak from the tribe and eliminate all other races. Go down into the deep tunnels and wage war with those who dare abide in the demesne of Shargaas. Be alert for weakness in the eyes of the chieftain, for his mistakes may spell your own doom."
